Immediately before or after the `@Transaction` annotation include the following:-

    @Query(&quot;&quot;)

e.g. 


    @Transaction
    @Query(&quot;&quot;)
    insertWeightAndCow(CowDbEntity cow, CommentDbEntity comment) {
        insert(weighting);
        insert(comment);
    }

Room then sees the function(s) as using the Database, due to the dummy query and wraps the function within a transaction (at least this used to be the behaviour).

This is according to https://developer.android.com/reference/kotlin/androidx/room/Transaction, as per:-

&gt; When used on a Query method that has a SELECT statement, the generated code for the Query will be run in a transaction. There are 2 main cases where you may want to do that:

&gt; If the result of the query is fairly big, it is better to run it inside a transaction to receive a consistent result. Otherwise, if the query result does not fit into a single android.database.CursorWindow, the query result may be corrupted due to changes in the database in between cursor window swaps.

&gt; If the result of the query is a POJO with {@link Relation} fields, these fields are queried separately. To receive consistent results between these queries, you also want to run them in a single transaction.

And then :-

&gt; Putting this annotation on an Insert, Update or Delete method has no impact because those methods are always run inside a transaction. Similarly, if a method is annotated with Query but runs an INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE statement, it is automatically wrapped in a transaction and this annotation has no effect. Room will only perform at most one transaction at a time, additional transactions are queued and executed on a first come, first serve order.

So the dummy query appears to fool Room into wrapping the otherwise ignored INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE (or whatever e.g. could be execSQL&#39;s, query or @Query annotated functions) into a Transaction.


And then 

&gt; The transaction will be marked as successful unless an exception is thrown in the method body.

That&#39;s the solution that worked (without @Transaction).

